===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# The state or condition of having [[weight]]; weight; [[heaviness]].
# The state or condition of being [[grave]]; [[seriousness]].
#: {{ux|en|I hope you appreciate the '''gravity''' of the situation.}}
# {{lb|en|music}} The [[low]]ness of a [[note]].
# {{lb|en|physics}} [[force|Force]] on Earth's surface, of the attraction by the Earth's [[mass]]es, and the [[centrifugal]] pseudo-force caused by the Earth's [[rotation]], resulting from [[gravitation]].
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2013-06-07|author=David Simpson
|volume=188|issue=26|page=36|magazine={{w|The Guardian Weekly}}
|title=[http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/2013/may/18/falling-upwards-richard-holmes-review Fantasy of navigation]
|passage=It is tempting to speculate about the incentives or compulsions that might explain why anyone would take to the skies in [the] basket [of a balloon]: perhaps out of a desire to escape the '''gravity''' of this world or to get a preview of the next;&nbsp;[&hellip;].}}
# {{lb|en|in casual discussion, also}} [[gravitation|Gravitation]], universal force exercised by two bodies onto each other (''gravity and gravitation are often used interchangeably'').
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2012-01|author=Michael Riordan|volume=100|issue=1|page=86
|magazine={{w|American Scientist}}
|title=[http://www.americanscientist.org/bookshelf/pub/tackling-infinity Tackling Infinity]
|passage=Some of the most beautiful and thus appealing physical theories, including quantum electrodynamics and quantum '''gravity''', have been dogged for decades by infinities that erupt when theorists try to prod their calculations into new domains. Getting rid of these nagging infinities has probably occupied far more effort than was spent in originating the theories.}}
# {{lb|en|physics}} [[specific gravity|Specific gravity]].

